answers.body_markdown:
There is no way to pass in named variable directly by function call. But you can, however, declare named variables with assoc array.

```php
&lt;?php

$src = &#39;src/...&#39;;
$arrayOfUseVars = array(
  &#39;var1&#39; =&gt; $var1,
  &#39;var2&#39; =&gt; $var2,
  &#39;var3&#39; =&gt; $var3,
);

function loadScript($src, $arrayOfUseVars)
{
    function($src) use ($arrayOfUseVars)
    {
       foreach ($arrayOfUseVars as $_name =&gt; $_value) {
         $$_name = $_value;
       }
       ob_start();
       include($src);
       $result = json_decode(ob_get_clean(),true);
       return $result;
    };
}
```

### Update

Just learn some new tricks. You can rewrite the above code with [compact](https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.compact.php) and [extract](https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.extract.php). This prevent the name collision with the `$_name` and `$_value` variables in the loop:

```php
&lt;?php

function loadScript($src, $arrayOfUseVars)
{
    function($src) use ($arrayOfUseVars)
    {
       // Note: Use EXTR_SKIP flag to skip creating
       // variable if the named variable exists
       extract($arrayOfUseVars, EXTR_SKIP);
       ob_start();
       include($src);
       $result = json_decode(ob_get_clean(),true);
       return $result;
    };
}

// use compact to pack $var1, $var2 and $var3 into an assoc array
// and send to loadScript for extract
loadScript(&#39;src/...&#39;, compact(&#39;var1&#39;, &#39;var2&#39;, &#39;var3&#39;));
```

Thanks to @KoalaYeung for this answer who work for me, here my final code who can keep variables I want inside the function (like the usage of &quot;use&quot;) : 


    function loadScript($src, $arrayOfUseVars = array())
    {
    	foreach($arrayOfUseVars as $name =&gt; $value)
    	{
    		${$name} = $value;
    	}
    	ob_start();
    	include($src);
    	return json_decode(ob_get_clean(),true);
    }
    loadScript(&#39;src/...&#39;, compact(&#39;var1&#39;, &#39;var2&#39;, &#39;var3&#39;));

